model_response: The number of participants experiencing dose-limiting toxicities is also important for evaluating the safety profile of BAY2862789. Dose-limiting toxicities are those that prevent further dose escalation or administration of the drug. Tracking these toxicities helps us determine the maximum tolerated dose of the drug and ensures participant safety.

The recommended phase 2 dose (RP2D) is determined by the dose that does not have any dose-limiting toxicities in more than 3 of 6 participants at a given dose level. This dose is considered safe and can be administered to more participants in the phase 2 part of the study.

The maximum concentration (Cmax) and area under the curve (AUC) of BAY2862789 are important measures of drug exposure. They help us understand how the drug is being absorbed, distributed, and eliminated from the body. These measures also help us predict the drug's efficacy and toxicity.

The secondary outcome measures for this clinical trial include assessment of tumor size, tumor marker levels, and other relevant biomarkers. These measures are used to evaluate the drug's efficacy and to monitor disease progression.

The objective response rate (ORR) is a measure of tumor response to treatment. It is calculated as the proportion of participants with a complete response (CR) or partial response (PR) divided by the number of participants with measurable disease at baseline. A complete response is defined as the disappearance of all target lesions. A partial response is defined as a decrease of at least 30% in the sum of the longest diameter of target lesions.

The disease control rate (DCR) is defined as the proportion of participants with either a CR, PR, or stable disease (SD) at 6 months. DCR helps us evaluate the extent of tumor control and disease stabilization in participants with solid tumors.

The duration of response (DOR) is measured from the date of the first documented response (CR or PR) until the date of disease progression or death due to any cause. DOR is an important measure of treatment effectiveness in cancer treatment.

Progression-free survival (PFS) at 6 months is defined as the time from the first dose of study treatment to the first documentation of disease progression or death due to any cause. PFS is an important measure of treatment effectiveness in cancer treatment.
Overall survival (OS) at 12 months is the time from the start of study treatment to the date of death due to any cause. It provides information on the treatment's ability to prolong survival.

The measures related to activation of effector T memory cells and ex vivo stimulated short-term activation of IL2 and interferon-gamma are prognostic indicators of response to BAY2862789. These measures help predict which patients are more likely to benefit from treatment with BAY2862789.

The physical items assess the impact of physical symptoms on daily life, such as walking, bowel and bladder function, and sexual function. Objective Response Rate (ORR) is a measure of the proportion of participants who experience a confirmed objective response to the therapy, which is defined as either complete response or partial response. Complete response means that the tumor shrinks and can no longer be detected by imaging or cannot be felt by physical examination. Partial response means that the tumor shrinks by at least 30% in a measurable area. Duration of Response (DoR) is the time during which the objective response lasts. Disease Control Rate (DCR) is the proportion of participants with either a complete or partial response. Time to Response (TTR) is the time from the first dose of therapy to the first objective response. Time to Progression (TTP) is the time from the first dose of therapy to the first documented disease progression or death due to any cause. Progression-Free Survival (PFS) is the time from the first dose of therapy to the first documented disease progression or death due to any cause. Overall Survival (OS) is the time from the first dose of therapy to death from any cause.
